title: LEGCO QUESTION NO.3 (Oral Reply)
question_text:
It is learnt that as soon
as the first confirmed case of Enterovirus 71 (EV-71) infection was found, the Hospital
Authority (HA) immediately notified the Department of Health (DH) to call for an
interdepartmental joint meeting. However, the DH did not convene the meeting concerned
until two weeks later. In this connection, will the Government inform this Council: (a) of the reasons why
the DH convened the meeting concerned two weeks after being notified by the HA; (b) whether efforts have

been made to trace the origin of the virus after the first confirmed case of infection was
found in Hong Kong; if so, what the results are; if not, why not; (c) whether instructions
have been given to all public hospitals and private clinics in Hong Kong, requiring them
to report suspected cases of infection to the DH, so as to monitor the spreading of EV-71
in the territory; if so, what the contents of the instructions are; and  (d) whether a review has
been conducted on any deficiency in the coordination between the HA and the DH on this

been conducted on any deficiency in the coordination between the HA and the DH on this
matter; if so, of the findings of the review and the measures to be adopted to improve the
coordination mechanism between the HA and the DH?
reply_text:
Madam President, (a) The Hospital
Authority (HA) informed the Department of Health (DH) on 26 June (Fri) of this year of the
first suspected case of Enterovirus 71 (EV-71) infection. According to quick test results
obtained in one of HA? hospitals, HA believed that the patient concerned had been affected
by EV-71. While DH was still conducting confirmatory test for the above mentioned case,
professionals from both parties held a meeting on 29 June (Mon), i.e. 3 days later, to

discuss matters relating to the testing of enterovirus. (b) Enterovirus is not a
new virus to Hong Kong. The group of enteroviruses include many types, EV-71 being one of
them. Over the years, diseases caused by enterovirus have occurred in Hong Kong and many
places worldwide. The main mode of transmission is through contact with faeces, saliva and
respiratory secretion of infected persons. According to the latest test results, the EV-71
discovered in Hong Kong is different from that discovered in Taiwan. DH will investigate each

discovered in Hong Kong is different from that discovered in Taiwan. DH will investigate each
suspected and confirmed case of EV-71 infection. According to the current studies, there
is no evidence indicating a particular type of premises as the sources where patients are
infected. (c) DH has implemented a
sentinel surveillance network since 14 June 1998 to closely monitor the occurences of
enterovirus infection and the spread of this virus. The sentinel surveillance
network now comprises the public hospitals in Hong Kong, DH? 63 General Out Patient

network now comprises the public hospitals in Hong Kong, DH? 63 General Out Patient
Clinics and 26 Private Medical Practitioners. They will submit to DH relevant information
for study once a case of EV-71 infection is found. DH has uploaded
information on enterovirus on the Internet since mid June this year. DH has also, at the
same time, disseminated such information to all local doctors through letters of the Hong
Kong Medical Association. In the letter, DH requested all medical professionals to
promptly inform DH of any unusual developments of enterovirus infection that come to their

promptly inform DH of any unusual developments of enterovirus infection that come to their
notice, e.g. a sudden increase of the number of infected cases. (d) HA and DH assume
different responsibilities in the handling of enterovirus infection. HA is mainly
responsible for clinical diagnosis and curative treatment, while DH is mainly responsible
for laboratory support and implementing the preventive and control measures against the
virus. There is no lack of co-ordination between HA and DH. HA's representative is
one of the members of the Interdepartmental Working Group on Enterovirus Infection headed

one of the members of the Interdepartmental Working Group on Enterovirus Infection headed by DH, working together with other organisations involved to eliminate the threat posed by enterovirus on the health of Hong Kong citizens.
